<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Ashanti's flotation valued at Pounds 1.67bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ashanti, one of the world's biggest gold mines, will have a market
capitalisation of up to Pounds 1.67bn after its flotation.
Yesterday the Ghanaian Government offered 17.9m shares in Ashanti Goldfield
Company, or just over 22 per cent. The price is expected to be between
USDollars 17 and USDollars 20 a share.
Ashanti, which reported profits after tax of USDollars 90.2m for the year to
end September, is seeking listings on the London and Ghana Stock Exchanges.
The company is also offering for subscription 3.5m new shares, or about 4.4
per cent.
The offer is intended to raise between USDollars 290m and USDollars 340m for
the Ghanaian Government after expenses, and between USDollars 47m and
USDollars 57m for Ashanti. After the offer the Ghanaian Government will own
around 31 per cent of Ashanti. Lonrho, which has a 45 per cent stake and is
not selling any shares, will have about 43 per cent of the enlarged share
capital.
Mr Sam Jonah, Ashanti chief executive, described the flotation as 'the
largest step in the Government of Ghana's economic liberalisation and
privatisation programme.'
Ashanti, which expects to produce over 1m ounces of gold in 1994-95, will
use the proceeds for working capital, to help finance capital expenditure
and for increased exploration. The group's net debt at January 31 was
USDollars 148.6m.
The Ghanian offer is expected to close on April 6, and the international
offer on April 18.
</TEXT>
