<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAR 94 / NW Water recruits from Tarmac
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER and ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
North West Water yesterday sought to lay to rest any anxieties over its
international expansion by appointing as its new chief executive Mr Brian
Staples, former head of Tarmac's contracting business.
He replaces Mr Bob Thian, widely credited with building North West's
international business. Mr Thian, a forceful manager, left in November
following what was reported as a 'difference in management style' with the
equally hands-on chairman, Sir Desmond Pitcher.
The City yesterday gave a cautious welcome to Mr Staples' appointment,
although as a divisional manager he is relatively unknown. 'He is a very,
very good risk analyser,' said one analyst. This, and his experience in
managing large sums of capital investment, would prove invaluable to North
West's international expansion, among the more aggressive in the UK water
industry.
Mr Staples, 48, became chief executive of Tarmac's construction division in
1992 and is highly regarded as a UK contractor within his industry. He had
been about to join the Tarmac main board. He said he intended to conduct a
strategic review at North West once he had learned his way around the water
industry. On the international side, he said North West would focus on
operating contracts, as opposed to the higher-risk contracting projects.
Sir Desmond said North West, which has suffered a number of executive
upheavals since privatisation in 1989, had sought to appoint a 'team
leader'.
Mr Staples was also arriving at a particularly 'important time for North
West as the regulatory review moves to completion'. The management of the
massive capital investment programme under the new pricing regime to be set
by the industry regulator this summer would be crucial to the group's
profits, he said.
Tarmac announced yesterday that, following the departure of Staples, it
plans to divide the construction business into two divisions. Mr Brian
Pellard, 51, managing director of Tarmac Construction Regions, will head the
contracting division. Steve Redding, managing director of Tarmac's
management division, will take charge of the professional services business
expanding its consultancy operations.
</TEXT>
