<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAR 94 / Schools back privatised inspectors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Most schools are happy with the new inspection system for England introduced
last September, says a report from consultants Coopers &amp; Lybrand.
The Office for Standards in Education (Ofsted) has contracted out the work
to new inspection companies to ensure that every school is inspected at
least every four years. In a survey of the first 100 schools inspected, 90
per cent reported that the inspections were well managed.
Two-thirds of the schools said the contract for inspection allowed adequate
coverage of their school's range of work.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand also said new 'lay' inspectors, whose presence was at
first strongly opposed by teachers, had 'played a useful role' and were
'well received in schools'.
Ofsted was also told, however, to reduce demands on schools for producing
information before inspections.
Professor Stewart Sutherland, chief inspector of schools, accepted the
report and announced that the number of inspection days for each primary
school would be reduced when their new four-yearly inspections started in
September.
The National Union of Teachers complained that schools' resources had been
excluded from the inspectors' remit. Mr Doug McAvoy, NUT general secretary,
said: 'That exclusion, which also covers class sizes, is a political
decision to enable the government to avoid the blame for shortfalls which
must lie at its door.'
A Focus on Quality, Ofsted Publications Centre, PO Box 151, London E15 2HN.
Free.
