<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAR 94 / Exchange proposes stake in Crest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Stock Exchange has proposed to its members that it should represent
their interests by taking a shareholding of up to 30 per cent on their
behalf in the new Crest paperless settlements system being developed by the
Bank of England.
The exchange has also proposed that it should interpret the needs of Crest
members to its technical managers.
Since the collapse of the Stock Exchange's proposed Taurus paperless
settlements system last March, the exchange has been seeking a role for
itself in the successor system being built by the Bank of England.
Sir Andrew Hugh Smith, Stock Exchange chairman, said in a letter to exchange
member firms late last week that ownership 'on the basis of a significant
minority interest would best contribute to the effectiveness of the
arrangements'.
Last month the Bank issued a consultation document on Crest ownership saying
that it did not believe any single company should own more than 10 per cent
of it and that no sectoral group should own more than 30 per cent. The
exchange is not interested in owning a stake as small as 10 per cent, it
said yesterday.
However, under these proposals ownership of a 30 per cent stake would
require Stock Exchange member firms to forgo their right to be individual
shareholders.
Sir Andrew said there will be a need for a management role to handle the
transition to Crest from the ageing, paper-based Talisman settlements system
currently in use and operated by the exchange, and 'to interpret the future
requirements of the owners and users to the operator and in managing market
changes'.
Sir Andrew said that at least in the early years of Crest operation the
exchange was the best body to do this.
But the Bank has made clear that it does not want any single company or
interest group to have a controlling role in Crest. In a paper issued last
month, the Bank said it wants a wide ownership base to avoid giving undue
advantage to any one commercial interest or to any one community.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
    P6289 Security and Commodity Services, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Services &amp; Services use.
</TP>
