<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAR 94 / Loophole in Irish Republic's extradition law to be closed by
end of next month
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A loophole in the Irish Republic's extradition law, under which an IRA
suspect was released from custody in Dublin yesterday, is expected to be
closed by the end of next month, Tim Coone writes.
Mr Anthony Gorman (above), wanted in Britain in connection with the 1992
killing of an army sergeant outside a recruiting office in Derby, was
released by a district court after the Irish state offered no evidence
against him.
New legislation in the republic will prevent IRA suspects blocking
extradition to Britain on serious criminal charges on the grounds that their
crimes are 'political'. The bill completed its Dail (parliament) stages with
little opposition, and is due to go to the Senate next week. Defence lawyers
for IRA suspects can argue now that possession and/or use of a non-automatic
firearm is a political offence, and non-extraditable under the Irish
constitution.
The Irish Department of Justice says the bill will be brought into force
once 'speciality' arrangements are in place between Ireland and the UK to
prevent a suspect being charged with a different offence to that upon which
he or she has been extradited.
Both governments are finalising arrangements which are expected to be ready
in time to coincide with the passing of the new extradition bill.
</TEXT>
