<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAR 94 / Tighter rules on Lecs called for
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Local enterprise companies (Lecs), the employer-led economic development
bodies, should be obliged to publish details of all grants they give to
businesses, Mr Campbell Christie, general secretary of the Scottish Trades
Union Congress, said yesterday.
Mr Christie said the recently introduced arrangement - whereby Lecs are
obliged to publish details of grants to companies in which a Lec director
has an interest - meant there was not the 'total openness' there ought to
be.
It also placed Lec directors whose companies were receiving Lec grants at a
disadvantage with their competitors. They had to disclose details of their
company's transactions with the Lec, but rival companies receiving grants
did not.
Mr Christie, who is on the board of the Glasgow Development Agency, one of
the Lecs, was giving evidence in Glasgow to the inquiry by the Scottish
select committee into Scottish Enterprise and Highlands and Islands
Enterprise, the parent bodies for the Lecs.
He said he believed in the local delivery of economic development, but was
concerned that too much power had been transferred by Scottish Enterprise to
the Lecs, creating tension between it and them.
For example, he said, Scottish Enterprise had given the Lecs responsibility
for helping defence companies diversify, instead of taking a strategic view.
An initiative to help the electronics industry was in the hands of the
Scottish Electronics Forum, which he called 'a self-help group' of companies
with little input from Scottish Enterprise or the Scottish Office Industry
Department.
Mr Christie also complained that there was no union representative on the
Scottish Enterprise board.
A public and private-sector partnership launched yesterday to promote
Somerset has set itself the target of helping to create 25,000 jobs by the
year 2000.
The Somerset Economic Partnership brings together the county and district
councils, chambers of commerce and industry and Training and Enterprise
Councils. It is the latest of a series of initiatives in the west country
designed to develop economic strategy and to lobby on issues such as
regional aid.
</TEXT>
