<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAR 94 / Straw fights back over council tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour yesterday stepped up its campaign for May's local elections by
claiming that three of the five highest council taxes in the country were
levied by Conservative authorities.
Mr Jack Straw, shadow environment secretary, accused the government of using
selective and inapplicable data to back its claim that Labour councils would
charge higher levels of council tax than the Conservatives next year.
Tackling what could be the most critical issue in the forthcoming local
elections, Mr Straw said the government had no basis for claiming that
Labour councils would charge an average of Pounds 129 more council tax than
Tory-controlled authorities.
The government arrived at this figure using the average rate of council tax
to be levied on properties in band C - valued between Pounds 52,000 and
Pounds 68,000.
Mr Straw argued that the calculation was deceptive because band C rates were
typically lower in Conservative areas where there was a preponderance of
homes in the higher-valuation bands, ranging from E to H.
'The Tories produced those council tax band C figures in a lame attempt to
prove that Tory councils were cheaper,' said Mr Straw. 'They convinced no
one, not even themselves.'
Using a different method of calculation - average council tax payments per
household - Mr Straw argued that Labour councils would charge Pounds 40 less
than the Conservatives next year, and Pounds 26 less than the Liberal
Democrats.
On this basis, a Local Government Chronicle survey of council taxes levied
in 205 shire districts found that Labour authorities charged an average of
Pounds 466.65 compared with Pounds 502.91 for Conservative councils and
Pounds 503.31 for the Liberal Democrats.
However, the same survey also suggests that several of the lowest-charging
authorities will be Tory-controlled. These include Wandsworth (Pounds
136.15), Wellingborough (Pounds 225.79), Westminster (Pounds 267.83) and
Rochester (Pounds 364.45).
Low-charging Labour authorities include Great Yarmouth (Pounds 375.50) and
Southampton (Pounds 395.82), the survey says.
