<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAR 94 / Further spending rise is expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The recovery in consumer spending is set to continue despite further
declines in consumer confidence ahead of next month's tax rises, says a
survey published today.
In its latest quarterly survey, PA Cambridge Economic Consultants reports
that consumer confidence is at its lowest level since March 1991, when the
survey began. A record number of households expects their finances to
deteriorate because of modest wages growth and next month's tax rises.
Despite this, planned spending on everyday items such as food and clothing
remains strong and is at its highest March level to date. The evidence for
durable goods is more mixed, although furniture and car purchase intentions
remain buoyant.
Mr Nick Mansley, senior consultant at PACEC, said: 'Evidence suggests that
people will want to carry on spending despite the tax rises being a major
concern, and most of this growth in consumption will come from a falling
savings ratio.'
The survey reports that house purchase intentions have increased slightly
but are still subdued.
Confidence in the government is at a record low. Of the 1000 respondents, 52
per cent said they had little or no confidence 'in the government's ability
to solve the pressing problems facing the country'.
The survey was conducted between February 26 and March 6.
</TEXT>
