<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAR 94 / Last-minute clause caused act's ambiguity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Yesterday's statement by Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry
secretary, resolves the confusion over an ambiguously worded clause inserted
into the 1986 Insolvency Act at the last minute.
In a 1985 case, Nicoll v Cutts, the courts ruled in favour of the receivers
and against a director who had sued them, claiming he was entitled to
compensation because he had not formally been dismissed.
The case was raised during parliamentary discussion on the Insolvency Act,
and a clause was introduced stating that a receiver who did not dismiss
employees at a company would be deemed to have adopted their contracts.
Until then, receivers had simply paid employees during the period for which
they were in charge of a company. Other employment costs - such as pay in
lieu of notice - ranked only as unsecured claims alongside other creditors'.
The 1986 law suggested that they would in any case become liable after 14
days for all outstanding employment obligations, including long-term service
contracts of the directors.
These claims have preference over money owed to unsecured creditors. In
administration, any remaining assets of a company would be paid to meet
these claims. In administrative receivership, the receiver would also be
personally liable for any remaining shortfall.
In 1987 the insolvency profession pushed through a test case - Specialised
Mouldings - which supported the action taken by receivers: that they were
not deemed to have adopted the employees' contracts if they wrote and told
staff that they had not done so. The Court of Appeal judgment on Paramount
two weeks ago appeared to overturn this ruling, arguing that all previous
employment rights should be honoured and ranked as priority claims ahead of
unsecured creditors unless a new contract had been drawn up.
As a result, insolvency practitioners began to lay off staff rather than
risk incurring substantial additional obligations and becoming personally
liable for any shortfall.
Mr Heseltine's statement yesterday ensures that future administrations and
receiverships will reinstate the practices adopted by practitioners until
now, and remove the personal liability of receivers to meet any shortfall.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
THREAT TO THE RESCUE CULTURE
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
 -What the Insolvency Act 1986 sets out
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  It makes receivers personally liable for any contract of employment
  'adopted' by them. If administrators 'adopt' a contract, employees get
  first call on assets.
  It recognises that administrators and receivers can contract out of
  personal liability by providing that they will not be deemed to have
  'adopted' a contract of employment because of anything they do or omit
  to do within 14 days of their appointment.
  It gives receivers the right to an indemnity against personal
  liability out of the assets of the company.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
 -How it was interpreted
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  Administrators and receivers interpreted the act to mean they had 14
  days after their appointment to dismiss employees or to negotiate new
  employment terms which exclude personal liability. This was endorsed
  by the High Court in February 1987.
  Receivers and administrators now issue letters to all employees within
  14 days of their appointment. These spell out that the company will
  continue to pay salaries buy they do not and will not adopt or assume
  personal liability in respect of contracts of employment.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
 -The case of Paramount Airways
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  The administrators issued such a letter to all employees but when they
  failed to find a buyer and dismissed all the employees, two pilots
  sued for wages in lieu of notice.
  The administrators argued they had not adopted contracts of employment
  because of the letter sent to employees exluding personal liability.
  The Court of Appeal said that 'where administrators continued
  substantially after 14 days to employ staff and pay them in accordance
  with previous contracts they would be held impliedly to have adopted
  those contracts.'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
 -What happens next
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  Insolvency practitioners and lawyers say the decision reverses the
  previous position and threatens the 'rescue culture'.
  If receivers could not exclude personal liability they would not risk
  trying to trade out of difficulty. Little alternative but to dismiss
  staff immediately.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9121 Legislative Bodies.
    P9211 Courts.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
