<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAR 94 / Welcome for Paramount legislation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Heseltine's statement in the Commons yesterday may have come too
late for the employees of Michael Mayes, the textile manufacturer based in
Rotherham, South Yorkshire.
Although emergency legislation will apply from this morning, Mr Lindsay
Denney, the receiver from accountants Touche Ross, warned late last night
that the company was already being wound down and that there was no buyer in
the wings. He said he had not yet made a final decision, but he expected to
make an announcement to the company's 140 staff by lunchtime today.
However, the insolvency profession in general welcomed the proposed
legislation. Mr Mark Homan, head of insolvency at Price Waterhouse and
president of the Society of Practitioners of Insolvency, said: 'We're very
pleased. This puts the law back to what is was before 1986. This is
excellent news.'
Mr Richard Brown, deputy director-general of the British Chambers of
Commerce, said: 'This is good news for jobs, and for those concerned with
the capacity of UK commerce and industry.
'(It) gives back to administrators the crucial ability to manage companies
back into solvency.'
The amendment came after two weeks' intensive lobbying from the profession.
Mr Denney had met Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and mentioned his case,
while the society held meetings with Whitehall officials and submitted a
report to Mr Neil Hamilton, minister for corporate affairs.
For some, the legislation was already too late. Mr Steve Hill, an insolvency
partner with Coopers &amp; Lybrand, said that since the decision, he had had to
lay off 12 employees at a small building company and six at a maggot farm.
There have been relatively few such cases in the two weeks since the
Paramount ruling in the court of appeal.
Mr Homan said he believed that banks may have held back from calling in
receivers since the judgment in order to wait for clarification.
Mr Heseltine's statement offers no relief to companies already in
receivership or administration, to which the Paramount ruling appears to
apply.
Mr Homan warned that this might lead to a freeze on future payments to
creditors in many companies while potential additional employment costs were
quantified.
The administrators of Paramount are likely to appeal their case to the House
of Lords, while other insolvency professionals are considering seeking legal
advice on their own cases.
However, one leading practitioner said: 'I think the urgency has gone out of
this. Now it is each practitioner for himself.'
Another practitioner warned that while the law would remove the burden of
additional employment obligations from receivers and administrators, these
costs remained in place for purchases of insolvent businesses under the
transfer of undertakings law.
</TEXT>
