FT  15 MAR 94 / ITN radio franchise bid unlikely
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Independent Television News has almost certainly decided not to bid today
for the third UK national commercial radio licence for a predominantly
speech-based service.
ITN, which had been planning a bid with Planet 24 - the independent
production company - is still interested in radio, but has been put off, it
is believed, by two factors. One is the uncertainty over precisely what
format the BBC is planning for its news and sport service on Radio 5, Five
Live. The other is the announcement by the Radio Authority that a fourth
national radio service is now an option.
Fears, particularly of an INR4, are likely to reduce the number of serious
bidders for the INR3 licence to four or five, though it could be developed
as an all-news and talk station.
There is also considerable doubt that either GWR, the Bristol-based radio
group, or London's Capital Radio, whose two licences are soon to be
re-advertised, will put in a bid. There is also growing doubt whether
Classic FM, a rumoured runner, will go forward.
'The phones are still red hot. Everyone is still talking to everyone else,'
said one radio industry executive, who added that some decisions may not be
taken until this morning.
Firm bidders include:
Associated Newspapers together with SelecTV and the Radio Trust, a
consortium of radio interests.
Apollo Radio, a consortium that includes Chiltern Radio, Radio 702 of
Johannesburg and two financial institutions.
A consortium led by Mr John Whitney, former director-general of the
Independent Broadcasting Authority.
LBC, a company that has little choice but to bid. The London commercial
broadcaster goes off the air in October, having lost its licences to London
News Radio.
