FT  15 MAR 94 / Gardiner re-elected leader of 92 Group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir George Gardiner, the Conservative MP who was rebuffed when he attempted
to advise the prime minister, was re-elected yesterday as chairman of the 92
Group of rightwing MPs.
Sir George, MP for Reigate, suffered a blow to his credibility as a leader
of rightwing opinion when Mr Major ended a consultation meeting after just
two minutes.
Mainstream Conservative MPs saw the brevity of the meeting as evidence of Mr
Major's unwillingness to be dictated to by Sir George, who was pressing for
more rightwing cabinet ministers.
Sir George, a leading Maastricht rebel, also suffered a defeat when he was
removed from the executive of the 1922 Committee of Conservative MPs after a
campaign by government loyalists.
However, rightwing MPs said Sir George had 'comfortably' beaten off a
challenge to his leadership of the 92 Group from Sir Anthony Durant, MP for
Reading West, who is regarded as more committed to Mr Major's leadership.
Sir George said he would call a meeting of the group, which has more than
100 supporters, to sharpen its approach. 'We've always been a loyalist group
and that will continue. Our efforts will continue to be devoted to helping
the government to regain its popularity,' he said.
Mr Major was said to be 'relaxed' about the election result. However,
government whips had hoped that election of Sir Anthony would reduce
friction with the 92 Group.
