<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAR 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
You might have thought that a dramatisation of a Sherlock Holmes short story
and an episode in a documentary series about life today in a Chinese country
town would have little in common. Actually the theme is precisely the same
in both: opium addiction. Both run from 9.00 until 10.00 so if you want to
compare and contrast you will have to use a video recorder.
In The Memoirs Of Sherlock Holmes (ITV) our hero (who is, of course, not
averse to narcotics himself) investigates the opium dens of Rotherhithe.
Phil Agland's documentary Beyond The Clouds (C4) looks at the way that
today's form of opium - heroin - is pouring into southern China, with the
town of Lijiang on the front line.
Horizon explains how the workings of a car radiator led a scientist to a new
theory about why humans walk upright: it is all to do with the need to keep
thinking machines (computers/brains) cool (BBC2 8.00). BBC1 launches yet
another new comedy series: Men Of The World stars David Threlfall (forever
Smike from 'Nicholas Nickleby' in my mind) as a travel agent (8.30).
