<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAR 94 / Crime wave costs retailers Pounds 2.3bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Crime cost retailers Pounds 2.3bn in the year 1992-93, with about 30 per
cent perpetrated by shop staff, a report published today by Nene College
School of Business shows.
The report, sponsored by Boots, Dixons, Tesco, Entertainment UK, Barclaycard
and US security systems manufacturer Sensormatic, is based on reports
provided by retailers responsible for almost a quarter of UK retail sales.
It provides further evidence of the extent of retail crime, after a British
Retail Consortium survey published in January estimated that it cost
retailers Pounds 2bn in 1993.
The report found that 'ordinary theft' by customers, staff and suppliers
totalled Pounds 1,916m - more than the BRC's figure of about Pounds 1,400m -
with other forms of robbery and crime accounting for Pounds 377m.
Employee theft accounted for about Pounds 690m, or just over 30 per cent of
losses, while customer theft totalled Pounds 1bn, or 43 per cent.
Theft by suppliers accounted for just under 10 per cent, or Pounds 225m, and
burglary for 7.7 per cent, or Pounds 177m. Credit and payment card fraud,
ram raids, smash and grab raids, cash snatches, other forms of robbery, and
criminal damage each accounted for less than 2 per cent of losses through
crime.
The report found the average level of theft was about 1.35 per cent of
retail sales, with the highest rates found in pharmacies and toys, video and
music stores, and the lowest in sports and footwear shops, and furniture and
textiles stores. Grocery stores were responsible for nearly a quarter of all
losses through theft, however, and department stores accounted for 19 per
cent.
Shrinkage, which includes theft and administrative error and wastage,
equalled about 24 per cent of all retail profits.
The report found that more than 80 per cent of UK retailers favoured civil
recovery programmes, similar to those operating in the US, where recovery
agencies are empowered to make shoplifters pay for thefts and levy exemplary
fines, without recourse to legal authorities.
National Survey of Retail Theft and Security 1994. School of Business, Nene
College, Moulton Park, Northampton NN2 7AL. Pounds 30.
</TEXT>
