<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAR 94 / Sainsbury downgrades managers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The supermarket group J. Sainsbury, which said on Friday it was cutting 650
jobs in its head and area offices, is stripping out layers of store
management in a pilot programme which staff fear could lead to further job
losses.
The company is phasing out section managers, who have responsibility for
particular areas of stores, in 25 outlets of various sizes around the
country. They will be replaced by new posts of assistant manager and team
leader.
The 350 section managers in the stores have been told to reapply for one of
the new posts by May 9 or take redundancy. Those not appointed to one of the
new posts will be offered alternative shop-floor employment, but their wages
will be guaranteed for only two years.
A section manager said: 'They are trying to get people to go. Two people's
jobs will be done by one person.'
Sainsbury insists that the move was 'not initiated as a cost-cutting
programme' but was aimed at improving efficiency and customer service. It
said the section manager's role had become 'often a very physical job and
not enough of a management role.'
The company will evaluate the programme in the autumn. If it is successful
it is likely to be extended across Sainsbury's 350 superstores, affecting
several thousand section and department managers.
The changes are not connected with the restructuring being carried out in
Sainsbury's head and area offices, which the group said on Friday would lead
to the loss of 650 jobs in the next six to eight months.
Annual savings from the redundancies and other initiatives are estimated at
Pounds 50m.
Sainsbury is likely to announce a provision of between Pounds 10m and Pounds
20m to cover restructuring costs when it announces current-year results in
May.
</TEXT>
