<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAR 94 / Minister attacks growth of seaside jobless hostels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday resisted its de-regulatory instincts in an attempt
to halt the trend towards the conversion of seaside hotels into social
security benefit hostels.
Mr David Curry, the local government minister, said hotel owners would have
to apply for council planning consent before using their premises as
hostels.
Mr Curry said: 'What is happening at present is that you can convert your
seaside hotel to a hostel which then houses benefit claimants without any
form of authorisation or planning permission.'
The shift, foreshadowed by Mr John Major in an interview with the Sunday
Express, is a response to the growing clamour from predominantly
Conservative councils for action to halt the influx of benefit claimants to
coastal resorts.
The councils, backed in recent months by vigorous lobbying from Conservative
MPs, argue that the influx is keeping away holidaymakers and business
visitors.
Mr Curry stressed that existing hostels would be unaffected and hotels
denied planning permission in future would have the right of appeal.
Ministers acknowledged privately that the measures - which would be in place
before the local elections - contradicted the government's commitment to cut
the burden of regulation on small business. But political benefits for the
government were judged to outweigh economic costs.
</TEXT>
