<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAR 94 / Accountancy agreement brings merger closer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK's six leading accountancy bodies have agreed in principle to a
radical restructuring of their operations in a move that could lead to
merger. This would give more than 200,000 members of the profession the
right to call themselves chartered accountants.
In a statement expected next week, the six professional bodies plan to
announce principles leading to rationalisation. Details of the agreement,
developed by a sub-committee chaired by Mr David Bishop of KPMG Peat
Marwick, are still being finalised.
Worries about smaller bodies being swallowed by larger ones, and concerns
about variable quality and strategy have prevented significant mergers since
the 1950s.
The idea of reducing the number of bodies was given renewed emphasis last
week when Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, said fewer
accountancy organisations would better serve members' interests and make
them more effective in lobbying government.
When the last radical proposals to merge the professional bodies failed in
1970, they created the Consultative Committee of Accountancy Bodies, which
has proved unsatisfactory.
The present accountancy bodies' sub-committee, chaired by Mr Bishop, has
agreed 14 principles of rationalisation, which will be tested on a sample of
the bodies' members.
The statement is expected to say that all the bodies accept the need for
change, and to set out a series of objectives for the accountancy profession
into the next century.
Until now, it has only been possible for members of the three chartered
institutes of accountancy to call themselves 'chartered accountants'.
More detailed debates about the structure of a rationalised profession will
begin, including the way in which education and training will be provided,
and the structure and governance of any merged bodies.
One of the more likely outcomes would be a federal structure, with separate
bodies representing all accountants in Scotland, Ireland, and England and
Wales. Each of the three bodies would include divisions catering for the
different interest groups, such as small and large firms, public practice
and accountants in business, and the public sector. A small, central body
with elected or co-opted members from the regional institutes would deal
with issues such as ethics, regulation, auditing standards, international
liaison, and some lobbying. Jobs would be lost among the 1,200 staff of the
different bodies.
Those most cautious about rationalisation are the Institute of Chartered
Accountants of Scotland and the Chartered Association of Certified
Accountants, which have stated their preference for an intermediate stage of
'harmonisation' before considering whether to permit full rationalisation.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
