<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAR 94 / First warehouse club opening
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK's first British-owned warehouse club, selling goods in bulk at
discount prices, opens tomorrow in Croydon, south London, Neil Buckley
writes.
Cargo Club, operated by UK cash-and-carry company Nurdin and Peacock, is the
second US-style warehouse club to open in Britain. The first was opened in
November at Thurrock, Essex, by Costco Europe, 60 per cent owned by the
largest US club operator PriceCostco, with partners Littlewoods of the UK
and France's Carrefour.
Cargo Club remains close to the original US concept of the warehouse club -
a broad but selective range in no-frills surroundings; grocery products sold
mostly in bulk quantities; and an annual membership fee of Pounds 25.
Mr Mark Riches, managing director (above), says Cargo Club has been
carefully tailored to British tastes and needs. 'We are trying to appeal to
a wider audience than Costco,' he said.
Cargo Club plans further stores this year in Wednesbury, West Midlands, and
Bristol, and four more stores in 1995, with an eventual target of 30. Costco
is building stores at Bushey, Hertfordshire, and in Liverpool.
</TEXT>
